<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-051-242 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 442 786</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Sept 30 1991 n661 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Broader or deeper? (thoughts on the new European democraciesbecoming full members in the European Community; Uncommon Market)(Column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woolnough, Roger.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Full acceptance of the newly democratized central European nationsinto the European Community (EC) as it now stands would beunsuitable and problematic.andP;  Such acceptance would raise thenumber of countries within the community from 12 to 24 or more,making the council system of unanimous decisions virtuallyimpossible.andP;  Similarly, the number of state-appointedcommissioners would rise from 17 to 30, and that could increasethe already burdensome problem of translating official ECdocuments into all the languages of the member states.andP;  Theprocedures within the European Parliament would also becomeproblematic as its number of deputies rose from 518 to around1,200.andP;  The possibility of the new democracies applying for ECmembership has heightened the question of whether the communityshould be broader or deeper.andP;  Broader membership would allow earlymembership for any European country that applies.andP;  A deeper ECwould work toward greater integration of political decision-makingand national institutions.andP;  The applicants will most likely begiven associate membership of some kind, leading to fullmembership in the future, and current members will continue withtheir own integration without hampering the community's futureenlargement.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     European Economic CommunityMembership ListOrganization StructureGrowthOutlookAnalysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>